  "prompt": "Is it correct to use the phrase \"revert back\" in a sentence? I hear it all the time and on occasion even on BBC!",
  "response": "The phrase \"revert back\" is generally considered redundant because \"revert\" means to return to a previous state or condition. The word \"back\" is unnecessary since \"revert\" already contains the meaning of returning. The correct usage would simply be \"revert\". However, despite its redundancy, \"revert back\" has become commonly used in informal contexts, and you may encounter it in everyday speech or writing. For formal writing and clear communication, it is advisable to use \"revert\" alone.",
